","Matfen, Northumberland, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, Anglie"},"da":{"1214–October 1275":"1214–oktober 1275","1204–Male":"1204–Afdød","1206–Male":"1206–Afdød","1214–1275":"1214–1275","1228–Female":"1228–Afdød","1236–Male":"1236–Afdød","1238–Male":"1238–Afdød","1246–1310":"1246–1310","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1185–1250":"1185–1250","from 1204":"1204","1275":"1275","ABT 1236":"omkring 1236","1185":"1185","ABT 1238":"omkring 1238","1250":"1250","1180":"1180","1228":"1228","1206":"1206","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1204":"1204","1214":"1214","1236":"1236","1246":"1246","1224":"1224","1310":"1310","October 1275":"oktober 1275","Fenwick, Northumberland, England":"Fenwick, Northumberland, England","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberlandshire, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Frankrig","Matfen, Northumberland, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, England"},"nl":{"1214–October 1275":"1214–oktober 1275","1204–Male":"1204–Overleden","1206–Male":"1206–Overleden","1214–1275":"1214–1275","1228–Female":"1228–Overleden","1236–Male":"1236–Overleden","1238–Male":"1238–Overleden","1246–1310":"1246–1310","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1185–1250":"1185–1250","from 1204":"1204","1275":"1275","ABT 1236":"circa 1236","1185":"1185","ABT 1238":"circa 1238","1250":"1250","1180":"1180","1228":"1228","1206":"1206","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1204":"1204","1214":"1214","1236":"1236","1246":"1246","1224":"1224","1310":"1310","October 1275":"oktober 1275","Fenwick, Northumberland, England":"Fenwick, Northumberland, England","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberlandshire, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Matfen, Northumberland, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, England"},"en":{"1214–October 1275":"1214–October 1275","1204–Male":"1204–Deceased","1206–Male":"1206–Deceased","1214–1275":"1214–1275","1228–Female":"1228–Deceased","1236–Male":"1236–Deceased","1238–Male":"1238–Deceased","1246–1310":"1246–1310","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1185–1250":"1185–1250","from 1204":"1204","1275":"1275","ABT 1236":"about 1236","1185":"1185","ABT 1238":"about 1238","1250":"1250","1180":"1180","1228":"1228","1206":"1206","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1204":"1204","1214":"1214","1236":"1236","1246":"1246","1224":"1224","1310":"1310","October 1275":"October 1275","Fenwick, Northumberland, England":"Fenwick, Northumberland, England","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberlandshire, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","Matfen, Northumberland, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Fenwick","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern) and Scottish: habitational name from either of two places in Northumberland or from one in Yorkshire, all of which are so named from Old English <i>fenn</i> ‘marsh, fen’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying dairy farm’. There is also a place in Ayrshire, Scotland, which has the same name and origin. This last is the source of at least some early examples of the surname: Nicholaus Fynwyk was provost of Ayr in 1313, and Reginald de Fynwyk or Fynvyk appears as bailie and alderman of the same burgh in 1387 and 1401. The name is usually pronounced ‘Fennick’.","History: The name was brought over from England by several forebears, including George Fenwick (1603–56/7), a colonist from Brinkburn, Northumberland. He was one of the group of lords and gentlemen to whom the earl of Warwick, president of the Council for New England, granted forty leagues of territory west of the Narragansett River. George took up residence with his family at Saybrook, CT, in 1639. John Fenwick of Bynfield, Berkshire, England, established himself at Salem, NJ, in June 1675, the first Quaker settlement on the Delaware."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":1,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":10,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":45,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas de Fenwick was born in 1214, in Matfen, Northumberland, England, his father, Sir Robert de Fenwick III, was 34 and his mother, Margaret de Coventry, was 29. He had at least 3 sons with Alice de Lucy. He died in October 1275, in Fenwick, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1214–October 1275":"1214–oktoober 1275","1204–Male":"1204–Surnud","1206–Male":"1206–Surnud","1214–1275":"1214–1275","1228–Female":"1228–Surnud","1236–Male":"1236–Surnud","1238–Male":"1238–Surnud","1246–1310":"1246–1310","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1185–1250":"1185–1250","from 1204":"1204","1275":"1275","ABT 1236":"umbes 1236","1185":"1185","ABT 1238":"umbes 1238","1250":"1250","1180":"1180","1228":"1228","1206":"1206","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1204":"1204","1214":"1214","1236":"1236","1246":"1246","1224":"1224","1310":"1310","October 1275":"oktoober 1275","Fenwick, Northumberland, England":"Fenwick, Northumberland, England","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberlandshire, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Matfen, Northumberland, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, England"},"fi":{"1214–October 1275":"1214–lokakuu 1275","1204–Male":"1204–Kuollut","1206–Male":"1206–Kuollut","1214–1275":"1214–1275","1228–Female":"1228–Kuollut","1236–Male":"1236–Kuollut","1238–Male":"1238–Kuollut","1246–1310":"1246–1310","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1185–1250":"1185–1250","from 1204":"1204","1275":"1275","ABT 1236":"noin 1236","1185":"1185","ABT 1238":"noin 1